	<article>
		<h2 class="heading" id="stripe">Stripe (Payment Processor) and Security</h2>
		<div class="content">
			<b>Security</b>
			<p>Stripe is the company we are using for handling payments.  They're great because (among other things) they handle 99% of the security involved in processing credit cards.  The other 1% has already been handled when I installed SSL - a technology that encrypts all data while browsing your site. </p>
			<p> <b>Luckily, all this means is that you don't have to worry about credit card fraud on your end.  HOWEVER:</b>
			
			<b>It's extremely important that you do not share your login information with anyone you do not trust. </b> </p>
			<p> All the encryption in the world won't work if someone has access via a legitimate login.  (Think of a castle that has a moat and huge walls but leaves the gate down.)  <b>Even then, no credit card information would ever be at risk, only your customers' names and contact information.</b>  A physical business certainly locks their doors when they pack up for the night and that's the same idea here. </p>
			<p> Okay, my little speech on security is over.</p>
			
			<b>Logging into the Stripe Dashboard</b>
			<p>While there will rarely be a need for you to log into your account at Stripe, you need to be aware of how to do it incase a credit card dispute occurs, if you want to issue a refund, manage what appears on customers' credit card statements, or a few other things.</p>
			<p>To login, click on 'Orders' in the top navigation menu.  Click on "Visit Your Stripe Account."  If you've previously logged in, you'll be taken to the Stripe Dashboard.  Otherwise you'll need to enter your login information. </p>
			
			<p>You can also login to stripe by visiting "https://manage.stripe.com"</p>
						
			<b>Chargebacks / Disputes</b>
			<p>A customer may dispute a charge on the rare occasion that their credit card is stolen or they do not recognize your charge on their statement.  You'll receive an email directly from Stripe if this occurs with information regarding the dispute and what you can do to challenge or accept it.  <b>Though this happens infrequently, it is one of the consequences of accepting credit and debit cards as payment</b></p>
			
			<p>At any rate, <%= link_to "This Stripe Help Article", 'https://stripe.com/help/disputes' %> does a fantastic job at detailing the process.  They are a great company and will definitely help you throughout the process should a customer ever dispute a charge.</p>
			
			<b>Refunds</b>
			<p>If you need to issue a refund to a customer, login to Stripe.  Click on "Payments."  On the next page click on "View all payments." </p>
			<p>There, you'll see the description for each payment which <b>will include the order id assigned on your website's backend - in the order section</b>  Identify the correct payment by the order id or the customer's name (which also appears in the description) and click on it.  There you'll see a button "Refund Payment" which you can click and issue a partial or full refund to a customer.</p>
			
			<b>Manage Other Account Options</b>
			<p>At the top of the Stripe Dashboard, you can click "Your Account" and then "Account Details."  Be very careful with the settings here.  You can change your login information, your business contact information, and what appears on your customers' credit card statement when billed."</p>
		</div>
	</article>
	
